# Symbols in the grammar are case-sensitive.
#
# This grammar uses a convention that
#    - terminals are lowercase          (president)
#    - preterminals are capitalized     (Noun)
#    - other nonterminals are all-caps  (NP)
#
# This convention just makes grammars more readable to humans.  Thus:
#
#    - When *you* are writing grammars, you should
#      follow this convention unless you have a good reason not to.
#
#    - But the  *program* should still work with grammars that don't
#      follow this convention.  So how can the program reliably tell
#      the difference between terminal and nonterminal symbols?  If
#      there is at least one rule for rewriting a symbol, then that
#      symbol is a nonterminal and should be rewritten.
#######################

# Rules for creating full sentences.

1   ROOT    PSS .   # PSS = Present Simple Sentence
1	ROOT	S .
1	ROOT	S !
1	ROOT	is it true that S ?     # mixing terminals and nonterminals is ok.

# The basic grammar rules.  Here's what the abbreviations stand for:
#    S  = sentence
#    NP = noun phrase
#    VP = verb phrase
#    PP = prepositional phrase
#    Det = determiner (sometimes called "article")
#    Prep = preposition
#    Adj = adjective
#    Nom = Nominative -> generally marks the subject of a verb or the predicate noun or predicate adjective, as opposed to its object or other verb arguments.

# --------  level 1 --------

1       PSS     NP LVP
0.5     PSS     NP Verb Conj Noun LVP
0.7	    S	    NP VP
0.5     S       DN VP
0.5     S       S Conj S
0.5     S       ProN VP Conj DN VP

# --------  level 2 --------

1       NP      Nom
0.6     DN      Det Nom

1       LVP     LVerb PSVerb DN
1       LVP     LVerb DN
1       LVP     LVerb NAVerb
1       LVP     LVerb Adverb NAVerb

1       VP      Verb
1       VP      Verb   DN
1       VP      Verb   Noun
1       VP      Verb   DN   Adverb
0.6     VP      Verb   NP   Adverb
0.7     VP      Verb   PP

# --------  level 3 --------

1       Nom     Noun
0.7     Nom     Adj Nom
0.25    Nom     Nom ConjN Noun

1       Verb    Verb
0.4     Verb    Verb   ConjV   Verb

1       PP      Prep DN
0.115   PP      Prep DN PP

# Vocabulary.  Your program can see that "ate" is a terminal
# symbol because there exists no rule for rewriting it.
# Any symbol that can rewrite as a terminal (or a string of
# terminals, like "chief of staff") is called a "preterminal."  Notice
# that a preterminal is a special kind of nonterminal.

# -------- VERBS --------
#
# LVerb = Linking Verb.
# LVerbP = Linking Verb Plural.
# NAVerb = No Action Verb
# PSVerb = Present Simple Verb
#
# The verb 'To be' can take a linking and an auxiliary form.
# In order to support sentences in the form of: Noun-LinkingVerb-No-Action-Verb
#
# source: https://www.dr.com.tr/ekitap/english-gramma-am-is-are-was-were-patterns-and-examples
# source: https://www.grammar.com/Five-Kinds-of-Verbs-An-Overview

# Verb-Directional (from what I understood, it is sort of a sub-set of transitive verbs).
1   VerbD   go
1   VerbD   travel
1   VerbD   look # Can also take "at"

1	LVerb   am
1	LVerb	is
1	LVerb	was
1	LVerbP	are
1	LVerbP	were

# Transitive Verbs
1	Verb	ate
1	Verb	wanted
1	Verb	understood
1	Verb	pickled
1   Verb    sighed
1   Verb    wanted
1   Verb    preplexed

1   PSVerb  eating
1   PSVerb  drinking
1   PSVerb  thinking

1   NAVerb married
1   NAVerb beautiful
1   NAVerb sad
1   NAVerb angry

# Intransitive Verbs
1   ITVerb  with
1   ITVerb  to

